```

GLOBAL FIX: Make the nullability/invariant explicit instead of exposing a raw public pointer. For example, make `next` private and provide a checked accessor:

```cpp
class Node {
public:
    int data;

    explicit Node(int value) : data(value), next_(nullptr) {}

    void setNext(Node* next) {
        next_ = next;
    }

    bool hasNext() const {
        return next_ != nullptr;
    }

    Node& next() {
        if (next_ == nullptr) {
            throw std::logic_error("Node::next called on node with no next");
        }
        return *next_;
    }

private:
    Node* next_;
};
```

Then the use site becomes:

```cpp
if (node3->hasNext()) {
    Node n = node3->next();
}
```

This prevents unchecked null dereferences from being scattered through the program and makes the list invariant clear: either a node may have no successor and callers must check, or the data structure should enforce that every node has a valid successor before exposing traversal operations.

